    "topic": "39. India Eliminates Trachoma Recognised by WHO",
    "subtopics": [
      {
        "subtopic": "WHO Certificate of Elimination of Trachoma",
        "content": "India achieved a major public health milestone by receiving the **WHO Certificate of Elimination of Trachoma** as a public health problem during the 78th World Health Assembly (WHA) held in Geneva [14]. This recognition highlights India’s success in tackling one of the leading causes of preventable blindness [14]. Trachoma is a neglected tropical disease (NTD) caused by Chlamydia trachomatis, spreading through contact with infected eye/nasal secretions or flies, and is a major cause of infectious blindness [14]. The Indian delegation to WHA was headed by Punya Salila Srivastava, Secretary, MoHFW [15]. The 78th World Health Assembly was held from May 19 to 27, 2025, with the theme 'One World for Health' [15]."
      }
    ]
